    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <p>Conrad J. Clippert (1834-1901) was the patriarch of the family, and came to the United States from Hesse-Cassell, Germany. He worked under R.H. Hall and learned the business of brick manufacture. He began his own company in 1876, and was eventually elected sheriff of Wayne County in 1880 and 1882. He later served as vice-president of the Central Savings Bank of Detroit, and served as an officer of the institution until his death. His children were George H., Charles F., William, Conrad II, Fred, Hattie, and Julius.</p>
      <p>George H. Clippert (1860-1925) worked in the railroad service before taking over the family business, renaming it in 1899 as the George H. Clippert &amp; Bro. Brick Company. He was quite active in Detroit, belonging to several organizations: the Detroit Builders &amp; Traders' Exchange (vice-president and president); Detroit Board of Commerce; Wayne County and Home Savings Bank (board of directors); Board of Control of the State Industrial Home for Girls (chairman); Union Lodge of the Masonic Order; Benevolent and Protective Order of the Elks; Harmonie Society; and the Detroit Athletic Club. His children were Edna (married to Charles Kennedy whose papers are also at the Bentley), Harrison F., Phyllis M., Helen M., and George F.</p>
      <p>Charles F. Clippert was a partner with George H. in joining with their father's firm in 1884 when the business became Conrad Clippert &amp; Sons. His children were Conrad J. III, Marie, Hermine A., and Ruth (married to Douglas Roby, whose papers are also at the Bentley).</p>
      <p>Harrison F. Clippert was in Engineering at the University of Michigan (class of 1911) though he did not graduate. He served in World War I under the 65th Coast Artillery Corps, spending some time in France.</p>
      <p>George F. Clippert attended the University of Michigan during the 1920's (where he was a member of the Delta Tau Delta fraternity), and went to the Junior Plattsburg Military Training Camp at Lake Champlain in 1918.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>The Clippert papers are divided into nine series, six of which are organized under individual family members. The other three deal with the Clippert Brick Company and various Miscellanea and Photographs.</p>
    </scopecontent>
